      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let's focus on the microbial biology, shall we?\n\nIn a sourdough starter, the wild yeast and lactobacilli have different enzymatic capabilities. The wild yeast, like Saccharomyces cerevisiae, has enzymes like invertase and glucanase that break down starches into simple sugars, which are then fermented into ethanol and carbon dioxide. The lactobacilli, on the other hand, have enzymes like amylase and gluconase that break down starches into glucose and fructose, which are then fermented into lactic acid.\n\nThe lactic acid production is a critical factor in the pH of the starter. As the lactobacilli produce lactic acid, the pH of the starter decreases, creating an acidic environment that favors the growth of the lactobacilli. This, in turn, can lead to an increase in the production of lactic acid, which can further lower the pH.\n\nIt's a bit like a seesaw, where the wild yeast and lactobacilli are constantly competing for resources and space. When the wild yeast is dominant, it can produce more ethanol and carbon dioxide, but the lactobacilli can out",
